The first virtual provider arrives in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite enriched, the Czech providers offer practically all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
However, there is something missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic to lower prices.
Per it will not be allowed to wait for a long time.
That the Czech mobile service providers work among the most expensive in Europe, we have often about it on Mobil.cz.
This was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which noted that the price for a SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the latest steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming fees, it is so likely to come to a paradox situation - for some customers of the Czech mobile service providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are the prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really makes a struggle.
Per it sounds paradoxical, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of much more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, are pleased to blame about the fact that there is extremely much competition on the Czech market.
This is often attributed to the chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who has often stated in the past that there is no place in the Czech Republic for another provider.
It is likely true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has very many chances (on the other hand, it is likely that he will hardly find frequencies).
But there is another option – a virtual provider.
The entrance of virtual providers to the mobile market brought a significant price decline, which the classic mobile providers also had to respond to.
Even before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market in the UK, there were similar voices as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
It does not take a long time to look for examples.
In February this we the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just a half year, this provider managed to gain more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the country’s fifth largest provider.
Behind mobilking is the financial group Penta, which in the Czech Republic owns, among other things, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more concrete target audience.
In order to work efficiently, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not require relatively high costs for the construction, operation and entertainment of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers typically profile themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap telephone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a fairly good chess to put on a non-clicked target.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
“Real guys choose Mobilking – the provider they like and to whom they can trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operating company of this virtual provider.
It’s hard to say if a similar concept as in Poland could be found in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer.”
In the Czech Republic there is no chance, the mobile providers say
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
“We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations don’t look very hopeful.
It’s more likely to come to a market entry of mobilking in other countries of our region,” said Jana Studničková, a spokeswoman for the Penta Financial Group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It indirectly confirmed that the current mobile providers in the Czech Republic are not very pleased with this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything to make sure there is no potential competitor.
Your interest in the launch of a virtual mobile service provider has been shown for a long time by the GTS Novera Group, which wants to take a further step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the earlier, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile service providers.
With some of them, we have already achieved negotiating progress,” said Pavel Kaidl, the group’s spokesman.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Non-official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an unbeatable wall of silence.
“At this point we do not assume that there is room for a full-quality virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has great specificities compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area,” Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2 said in a statement for Mobil.cz.
The specifications of the Czech market are also highlighted by other providers.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds, in rare consistency with O2’s statement: “So far we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on.”
And she adds: “T-Mobile’s network will hardly show up a virtual provider by the end of the year.
At this point, we need to have a concrete offer to think so short-term.”
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the field of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we see as the best from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is looking for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The behavior of the mobile service providers is easy to understand, another provider calls more competition, this would lead to lower prices and thus also a decline in profits.
So why should we make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
That the providers can pull on a string, when it comes to something, also indicates the long way around the formation of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ came from the time when U:fon came to the market from the company T-Mobile.
This is also demonstrated by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
Now, however, U:fon is right as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová noted: “The competitive field of the mobile market has recently also been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile service provider.
Given the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new actor would pose high demands to the market itself and, above all, its services.”
However, in view of this approach, the mobile service providers are surprised by the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which in the Czech, unfortunately – unlike the UK and other highly developed countries – has no competence to interfere with economic competition.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, referred to this whole problem with its very typical attitude.
“The entry into the market of a virtual mobile service provider would be possible after a contract between a mobile service provider and a virtual service provider has been concluded on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
Until now, such a contract has not been concluded, as the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not interesting enough for the classic providers,” said Kristián Chalupa from the UOHS Department of Foreign Relations in his response to our request.
The representatives of the providers would not be surprised by such a formulation.
From an authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, ensures that no one abuses its position on the market, this is more than questionable.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the abroad where virtual providers work quite normally, it is to be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price decrease in mobile telephone services."
Probably, however, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price decrease are not the interests of the UOHS.
Really shocking in this case is the almost already touching consensus of the three mobile service providers, which arises from their reactions.
The question of whether it really is only a coincidence is on the hand.
Just like the absolute same price of gasoline at the gas stations is only a coincidence and the result of a harsh competition.
“The authority has not found any signs indicating an anti-competitive action in this matter, and therefore it has no reason to interfere in any way in the matter.
None of the providers have a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary tools to open the mobile market for virtual providers are likely to lack the telecom regulatory authority," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications from the point of view of economic competition is a single market.
In such a market, of course, no one of the Czech mobile providers has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - for the entry into the market of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile service provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that he necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if you don’t agree with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the UOHS that three mobile providers are acting similarly.
The complaints of a number of stakeholders (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) indicate that they face very similar obstacles when negotiating with all suppliers.
The dismissal of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the newly adopted Novelle of the Telecommunications Act has failed to extend the competence of ČTÚ to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS need to know this very well, but they probably have other interests.
It can be when no one looks.
In the first place, the functioning of any pseudovirtual providers, of which there are equally several in the Czech mobile networks, remains ignored.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but that are only partly public.
These are usually companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Its own mobile telephone services, for example, offer Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The lists of prices of these companies usually reach only selected.
The joke of the thing is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will then receive special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile service providers prohibit a similarly performed re-sales.
"If there are cases you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to an end of cooperation with the corresponding society," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not happen in the responsibilities of the mobile providers.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator is opposed to such action.
The activities of these companies do not result in overlooking profits, and at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they will not be affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický notes possible problems: “The law allows such speculations, despite all, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they can’t have it fully as the normal customers of the mobile service provider.”
But that alone, at least, should be strange.
Also, another question is opened for the UOHS.
Mobile providers close their eyes to such an action, why do they lock themselves against a virtual provider?
It is to add that the ÚOHS has a fairly strong competence to discover such activities, and if it does not want, it does not have to satisfy with the declaration of the providers, they knew nothing about it and their business conditions would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As the text has been emphasized several times, the market entry of virtual providers brought a significant price decline in the various services.
Practically in all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence practically more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical – a too small, or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But in the highly developed countries, it is just in these moments that regulatory bodies are struggling to protect the interests of the mobile service providers, but those of their customers.
Whether it was through formal actions or an informal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and that followed more.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities take the whole case as a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that uncertainty in the competencies in these cases is more than favorable.
But we don’t throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is true and a virtual provider will soon appear, the Czech mobile market may soon be back in motion.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the UOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other stakeholders.
And the Czechs will finally not call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
