Prague transport companies will transport on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, 1 October 2008, will enter the history of the Prague transport operations as a date on which the first passengers enter a metro, railway or bus, who carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper car.
These can now be purchased by about a hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, a 90-day or an annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously play it on their chip card, in the information centers and branches of the transport operations at the metro stations Museum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons are available on the Internet on the website of the transport agencies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than 400 customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use the internet sales can really forget the output window in the metro stations, where they have until now had to regularly wait in long serpents on their paper chains.
You buy the coupon on the Internet, which is played on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
“In these places, a switch with trained staff is also available to the travellers, which advises those interested in online shopping and also plays the coupon on the card,” said project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coups can also be played on self-control machines on the Opencard, which are placed in some metro vestibules.
How do these machines look like?
They are red, reminds of tickets, the passengers may have noticed them already in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today there are five of them in the city, but it is expected to be eighty until the end of the year," Opatrný added.
The coupon is controlled by an automatic driver instead of the driver
Operating the machines that will work from tomorrow is easy.
You just have to introduce the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon is played by itself.
The electronic coupons will be valid not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburb trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which mainly the inhabitants of the municipalities of the region of Middle-Böhmen enter the capital.
“In the trains that belong to Prague integrated traffic, the trains accompanyers have readers with which they can check the validity of the coupons by time and zone,” explains Filip Drápal from the organization Ropid the check-in control.
The suburb buses have card readers on the box with the driver.
When entering, the chip card must not only be displayed to the driver, but the open card must be attached to a marked place on the side of the box.
Thus, the driver controls the validity of the cupons played.
“Will a passenger check the validity of the played coups, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information,” Drápal said.
A passenger who doesn’t drive by suburban buses and doesn’t know when the voucher’s validity ends can turn to the self-control machines where the vouches are played on the card.
Here the information on the validity of its documents is displayed on the device's display.
