Debate on bilingual education: education in an English-speaking environment
In this edition of the "Education Watch", Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of the candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, chief academic staff in California Studies and chief director of the Department of Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as well as you think: Why the middle class needs a school choice."
Talking to the Spanish voters is a complicated task.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentioned that “the likelihood for African-American and Hispanic students to graduate school successfully is lower than for white students” – which is true.
To close this performance gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among others, a bilingual transitional phase in education for those who learn English first.
However, the question to Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in other languages than English, is contrary to his interest in reducing the distance in school services.
Let’s take the example of “Sixth Street Prep”, a primary school in the east of Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Spanish and come from low-income families.
More than one-third of students, many of whom have just recently been in the country, learn English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, amazing 100 percent of fourth-class students passed the state exam in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93% of children from the fourth school year were well assessed in the English exam.
This amazing success was achieved by other methods than those that were preferred by Obama.
The Sixth Street School focuses on review and exercise, on constant control of knowledge and an attitude that does not tolerate any exceptions.
Moreover, the school practices the approach according to which education is conducted in an English-speaking environment. That’s exactly what Obama should consider, says school leader Linda Mikels.
This approach emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in vocational teaching.
Mrs. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school would have a remarkable success with a student who had only come from Mexico shortly before.
