Drivers who may be reclaimed due to the alcohol level will have to install the ‘Alcolock’.
The authority orders that the driver who had three official penalties for the alcohol level installs this system in his car, which prohibits him to start the car in a drunk state.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the report of the General State Prosecutor's Office.They say it is a pilot project that will take a year.
The purpose is the resocialization of the driver, which is why he gets a course for the education of traffic behavior.
In addition to the General Prosecutor's Office, according to experience, the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for Automotive Safety will also participate.
According to statistics, between 30-75% of the drivers who have been shown more than once because of driving under alcohol influence have returned to drive.
The ‘alcolock’ would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the breathed air and prevents the start of the car when the driver has done the alcohol test; or when a alcohol concentration is detected that is higher than permitted.
It costs more than 1 000 euros, the costs will be borne by the one who imposes the sanction.
In this context, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 has shown that cars equipped with these devices already in the first year after its introduction prevent up to 65% of violations.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved annually.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to interfere with this behavior before it becomes a crime.
And in order to facilitate their implementation, a legislative reform can be achieved in the usual way, and yet a reform of the basic law is required, which is necessary for the prosecution process.
Still, the device is on the Spanish markets, not available in any store, although it has already been built-in in some commercial vehicles and vehicles of public transport.
Exactly tomorrow, the House of Representatives will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses.
