Speaking in sleep
Some children talk at night.
I do not mean those who wake up and tell us what happened the day before, but the children who speak during sleep.
When it happens to you for the first time, in the best case you will be scared, but in reality it has no meaning.
This is a positive sleep disorder, which is called speech in sleep.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
Certainly, more than one of you has been told that you’ve talked at night.
This phenomenon may occur occasionally (one time in life, for example, as during high fever), or regularly (every day, once a week, once a month), the next day the child can remember nothing.
There is no one reason that causes this appearance.
Often, connections with other phenomena in sleep are sought, such as night dreams, panic anxiety at night, enuresis noctura (night sleep), speech in sleep, but there is no reason for it.
As we have mentioned earlier, it can be very high fiber, stressful situations or overload.
In any case, this is a slightly investigated phenomenon.
The frequency with which it occurs is very variable.
It can be that one speaks quietly in a single word, flirting, or it can be quite the opposite (writing, crying, long discussions).
In cases where the expression is very intense, it is recommended to observe the child and consult with a specialist to check if there is a problem that causes anxiety and occurs in this way.
We’ve said it’s a positive disorder, so it’s not treated whether it’s associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, with sleep apnea or with stress).
What you can do is perform a series of simple preventive measures:
