In 1999, a much more accurate technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the Nucleic Acid Tests (NSTs), which allow it to prove the occurrence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not the antibodies against the virus, as it was in the previously used tests.
The NSTs enabled it to shorten the incubation time that occurs between the time at which the person was infected and when the first viruses can be demonstrated in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a period of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that some donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements allowed to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
