The Psychology of Supply - or Why We Are Ready to Pay More
In sales, the buyers tend to spend more and thus exaggerate the default.
Neurologists and economists from the University of New York have now managed to discover the neurological and economic foundations of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people don't want to beat themselves in a competition, such as a sale on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even exaggerated prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play lottery, while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, however, an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain cord, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the opponent's overwhelming played a key role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price rise could be explained by avoiding a streat overreaction.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have further conducted investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should offer against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the actual value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward for the event that they appear as a winner out of the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, that the emphasis on one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
As proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the group playing against losing were willing to make higher bets than those in the control or win group.
"These findings cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These behaviors, in fact, have found the behavior observed at auctions so far only with the pleasure of winning or risk avoiding.
The contradiction between these two theories was solved thanks to the imaging neurological methods, so we are now ready for a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, Professor of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you visit the doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected in this country is estimated to be a hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because the patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases triggered by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and yellowness are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogens, hepatitis viruses spread in two different types: with hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated foods or water), with hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, sperm secretion or sperm).
Travellers are recommended a vaccine against the viruses A and B at all, against the virus C there is no vaccine.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and swelling.
After that, yellowness occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes bright, the urine dark, and recovery can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year around 1 million people worldwide die from the far more severe diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected are in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people don’t even know about their illness, as the pathogen destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular inspections, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who have undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease is already demonstrated by routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognized in time, the disease is healable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby preventing the risk of infection and preventing the formation of cancer.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, 2004 for the first time organized by patient representations worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, its occurrence and the importance of early detection.
