Intelligent car imitates the flight of the Hummel
What would be the best way to develop new accidents prevention technologies if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At the CEATEC in Japan, a stunning project was presented, inspired by Nissan’s hummel engineers to create new accidents prevention systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the autobot-controlled biomimetic system of the BR23C type, a mini-car equipped with the properties of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that prevents any collisions.
In the flight, each beer forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protection shield", Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, said at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bees, which can see in any direction and in an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
To understand the function of the composed eye, the researchers approached the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a face field of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor to board, which immediately starts the collision prevention process.
The obstacle is recorded in seconds, and the autobot immediately changes the course, similar to the bees’ movement by turning the tyres around the corresponding corner.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
"If it wasn't so, the autobot could not react quickly enough to escape the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the autobot project.
The system must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innerest and most vulnerable part of the shield – a layer that is still considered inevitable within accidents.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they escape other bees.
This must be done in a short of a second.
However, the escape, unlike the bees, can not be up, down, or even diagonal - it can only be two-dimensional, and it can only be in the direction of the rotability of the tyres.
While the bees here have infinite possibilities to escape other bees, the researchers in the car robotic could only use the rotating movement, as well as acceleration and braking.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to save them.
This device needs to process only a few inputs per second and respond to them accordingly.
It doesn’t have to save them, or by using previous maneuver to produce an intuitive, logical reaction, so it continuously requires just a handful of KB memory.
It does not require any Gigabyte and Megabyte heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision prevention technology, which, according to Nissan’s estimates, will be serially in production over the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously driving the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the destination.
